    {
      "Id": "00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000",
      "ConversationId": "00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000",
      "Role": 1,
      "Content": "\u0060\u0060\u0060go\npackage main\n\nimport (\n\t\u0022fmt\u0022\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n\tvar total float64\n\tvar expense string\n\n\tfor {\n\t\tfmt.Print(\u0022Enter an expense (or \u0027done\u0027): \u0022)\n\t\tfmt.Scanln(\u0026expense)\n\n\t\tif expense == \u0022done\u0022 {\n\t\t\tbreak\n\t\t}\n\n\t\t// Attempt to convert the input to a float64\n\t\tvalue, err := fmt.ParseFloat(expense, 64)\n\t\tif err != nil {\n\t\t\tfmt.Println(\u0022Invalid input. Please enter a number or \u0027done\u0027.\u0022)\n\t\t\tcontinue\n\t\t}\n\n\t\ttotal \u002B= value\n\t\tfmt.Printf(\u0022Total: %.2f\\n\u0022, total)\n\t}\n\n\tfmt.Printf(\u0022Final Total: %.2f\\n\u0022, total)\n}\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n\nThis is a very basic expense tracker. It prompts you to enter expenses, adds them to a running total, and allows you to finish when you\u2019re done.  Do you want me to explain any part of the code in more detail?",
